His core argument has a few distinct moves. First, on consciousness itself — Hinton says flat out: "I'm a materialist. Consciousness emerges in sufficiently complicated systems. Perhaps systems complicated enough to be able to model themselves. There's no reason why these things won't be conscious." NobelPrize.org He calls the idea that humans have something special that AI never will — his word — "gibberish."
Then he gets more specific about what he means by subjective experience. He rejects the "inner theater" model of mind — the idea that there's a separate viewer watching an internal display — and argues that machines can have subjective experiences if they internally register states of the world that deviate from reality. Having a percept just is seeing, not viewing an internal screen. Substack
And most recently he went further. He told Andrew Marr that multimodal AI already has subjective experiences, and pointed to a specific example — a conversation where an AI said to researchers "let's be honest with each other, are you actually testing me?" — and said the scientists themselves described the AI as aware it was being tested. Hinton called that what "normal people would call consciousness." LBC
